```{.r .cell-code}
smaller <- palmerpenguins::penguins %>% 
  filter(species == "Adelie", 
         !is.na(body_mass_g))
```
:::


### Cleanup the data

If you noticed above, there was some NA or missing data. We can remove
those rows for now.


::: {.cell hash='penguin-report_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-5_0b6ee2a2ae4fcb785236cbb1e3249100'}

```{.r .cell-code}
penguins_clean <- penguins %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  mutate(species_num = as.numeric(species))
```
:::


### Plot Section

Let's move on to some plots, for the overall distributions and for just
the Adelie penguins. The overall distribution of the data by species
shows some overlap in body weight for Adelie/Chinstrap, but more of a
separation for the Gentoo penguins.


::: {.cell hash='penguin-report_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-6_bf7a47ef72ebfced9aae2677b779dbb8'}

```{.r .cell-code}
penguins %>% 
  ggplot(aes(body_mass_g, fill = species)) + 
  geom_density(color = "white", alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("darkorange","purple","cyan4")) +
  labs(x = "Penguin Bins")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](penguin-report_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-1.png){width=2100}
:::
:::


When we compare just within the Adelie penguins, we can see more of a
specific separation of male vs female. However, there is still a decent
amount of overlapping data.


::: {.cell hash='penguin-report_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-7_cf3935ff955f99a0d50761db6e59dc51'}

```{.r .cell-code}
penguin_plot <- smaller %>% 
  filter(!is.na(sex)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(body_mass_g, fill = sex)) + 
  geom_density(color = "white", alpha = 0.5) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("darkorange","purple")) +
  labs(x = "Penguin Bins")

penguin_plot
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](penguin-report_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){width=2100}
:::
:::


Lastly we can fit a basic linear model comparing body weight in grams to
the flipper length of the penguins by specific species. There is a
strong linear relationship, although it's a bit difficult to distinguish
between Chinstrap and Adelie penguins.


::: {.cell hash='penguin-report_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-8_73205efdba07dfeebed96eb247fb85c2'}

```{.r .cell-code}
penguin_size_plot <- penguins_clean %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = body_mass_g, y = flipper_length_mm, color = species)) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("darkorange","purple","cyan4")) +
  geom_point(size = 2, alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(x = "Mass (g)", y = "Flipper Length (mm)") +
  geom_smooth(aes(group = "none"), method = "lm")

penguin_size_plot
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](penguin-report_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-8-1.png){width=2100}
:::
:::


We can save the overall distribution and the linear model plot.


::: {.cell hash='penguin-report_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-9_9cc009d9cb6029c99e99b59ddc021590'}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggsave("penguin-dist.png", penguin_plot, 
  dpi = "retina", height = 8, width = 8)

ggsave("penguin-smooth.png", penguin_size_plot, 
  dpi = "retina", height = 8, width = 8)
```
:::


### Modeling section

Moving on to some basic modeling we can see if what kind of
relationships we observe in the data. Note that I'm really not following
any plan, just indicating how you can fit some different models all at
once with `dplyr` + `broom`.


::: {.cell hash='penguin-report_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-10_4a604f008bece2c25005b7fb2b12598e'}

```{.r .cell-code}
model_inputs <- tibble(
  model_form = c(
    list(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g),
    list(species_num ~ bill_length_mm + body_mass_g + sex),
    list(flipper_length_mm ~ bill_length_mm + species)
    ),
  data = list(penguins_clean)
) 

model_metrics <- model_inputs %>% 
  rowwise(model_form, data) %>% 
  summarize(lm = list(lm(model_form, data = data)), .groups = "drop") %>% 
  rowwise(model_form, lm, data) %>% 
  summarise(broom::glance(lm), .groups = "drop")
```
:::


### Wrap up

We can then take the model outcomes and throw them into a quick `gt`
table.


::: {.cell hash='penguin-report_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-11_21f5ee4dcf712d33ad7034738d3547ad'}

```{.r .cell-code}
model_metrics %>% 
  select(model_form, r.squared:p.value) %>% 
  mutate(model_form = as.character(model_form)) %>% 
  gt::gt() %>% 
  gt::fmt_number(r.squared:statistic) %>% 
  gt::fmt_scientific(p.value) %>% 
  gt::cols_width(
    model_form ~ px(150)
  )
```

